<p>Profit margin is the single most important metric for any business. It tells you what percentage of revenue you actually keep as profit — after all costs. Whether you're a freelancer pricing a project, a shop owner reviewing finances, or an investor evaluating a company, understanding profit margin calculation is essential.</p>

<h2>Types of Profit Margin</h2>
<p>There are three main profit margin metrics, each providing different insights:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Gross Profit Margin:</strong> Revenue minus Cost of Goods (COGS) — shows manufacturing/procurement efficiency.</li>
    <li><strong>Operating Profit Margin (EBIT Margin):</strong> After deducting operating expenses (salaries, rent, utilities) — shows operational efficiency.</li>
    <li><strong>Net Profit Margin:</strong> After all expenses including taxes — the true bottom-line profitability.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Profit Margin Formulas</h2>
<div style="background:#f4f6f8;padding:20px;border-left:5px solid #4f46e5;margin:20px 0;border-radius:8px;">
    <strong>Gross Profit Margin (%) = ((Revenue − COGS) / Revenue) × 100</strong><br><br>
    <strong>Operating Profit Margin (%) = (Operating Profit / Revenue) × 100</strong><br><br>
    <strong>Net Profit Margin (%) = (Net Profit / Revenue) × 100</strong>
</div>

<h2>Step-by-Step Example</h2>
<p>A clothing boutique in Mumbai earns ₹15,00,000/month.</p>
<ul>
    <li>COGS (fabric, tailoring) = ₹8,00,000</li>
    <li>Operating Expenses (rent, salaries, marketing) = ₹4,00,000</li>
    <li>Tax = ₹75,000</li>
</ul>
<ol>
    <li>Gross Profit = ₹15,00,000 − ₹8,00,000 = ₹7,00,000</li>
    <li>Gross Margin = (7,00,000/15,00,000) × 100 = <strong>46.7%</strong></li>
    <li>Operating Profit = ₹7,00,000 − ₹4,00,000 = ₹3,00,000</li>
    <li>Operating Margin = (3,00,000/15,00,000) × 100 = <strong>20%</strong></li>
    <li>Net Profit = ₹3,00,000 − ₹75,000 = ₹2,25,000</li>
    <li>Net Margin = (2,25,000/15,00,000) × 100 = <strong>15%</strong></li>
</ol>

