<h2>How to Improve Your Profit Margin</h2>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Increase average order value:</strong> Upselling and bundling raise revenue without proportionally increasing COGS.</li>
    <li><strong>Reduce COGS:</strong> Negotiate better supplier prices, optimise inventory to reduce waste.</li>
    <li><strong>Cut discretionary spend:</strong> Audit subscriptions, renegotiate rents, reduce advertising spend that doesn't convert.</li>
    <li><strong>Focus on high-margin products:</strong> Analyse per-product margins and promote the most profitable items.</li>
    <li><strong>Raise prices strategically:</strong> A 5% price increase on stable demand can improve margins dramatically.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="faq-section">
    <div class="faq-item"><h3>Is a higher profit margin always better?</h3><p>Higher margins are generally better, but some industries intentionally operate on thin margins with very high volumes (grocery, fuel retail). Context matters — compare within your industry.</p></div>
    <div class="faq-item"><h3>What is a healthy profit margin for a startup?</h3><p>Startups often operate at negative margins initially due to high customer acquisition costs. A 10%+ margin is considered healthy once product-market fit is established.</p></div>
</div>

